The live part ends at 1:12, though, then the pre-recording kicks in. The sound technician was supposed to shut down the mic when the recording started, but the mic was still open. He figured his mistake when the recorded vocal kicked in and pulled back the mic fader on the mixer, because the mic picked up her singing in a different pitch and possibly some sound bits from the stage speakers (at 1:21). You can actually hear the quick fade-out. Also, they put a somewhat heavy reverb effect on the mic line for the live part, whereas the vocal effects on the recording are rather light. Her voice sounded rather soft in the live part (or the live mic she used was less sensitive), but her vocal on the pre-recording was pretty loud/powerful. She's a really good singer, but this wasn't a 100% live performance.

Fun fact: The meaning behind this song stems from when she was a street performer in Australia. You are required to have a permit in order to do so, and a lot of the "customers" were known for being super rude and treating her like she was some zoo animal who was meant for their amusement.   She said that they made her feel as though they were saying "Sing, monkey". However, in order to make the song slightly less personal, she changed it to "Dance Monkey", rather than "Sing Monkey", which is what she was actually doing.

â€‹Â @elnora1469Â   Not making a big deal out of it... would be if she would shrug her shoulders at people shouting.. and carried on performing and perhaps be inspired by those who did express sympathy for what she offered.   Making a song out of a negative experience  as reflected in this song.. (and delivering it with such a forcefully pathetic childish and affected voice at that) ..  obviously IS making a big deal out of it. Which is a good thing in a way, certainly a testimony to her creativity and it turned out to be her claim to fame. Good on her! Doesn't make the inspiration, she said to have, convincing or "just".   I guess she had a tough time managing expectations of her audience. She could have said; "I only sing originals..  and I hope you like them".. or "I have a very strict list of songs.. and won't stray away from it.. but I'll take some of your suggestions home and perhaps work them out".. or words to that effect. Either way; she's not there to present "her person".. but out there trying to please people who pass by on the streets with her material she brings as a singer.. and make money in the process. We're made to believe the audience was rude.. because she says so.. but how good (or bad) was her actual performance at the time? How did she engage with her audience?  In short: it's a stretch of rhyme and reason to downplay the legitimate reasons to put her sincerity and authenticity up for discussion.   On the "toughness" out there..:  nobody asked for street buskers, they're not forced to so;  they're imposing themselves on others by choice.  If you want to sling your stuff out there on the streets.. you can expect to get something thrown back at you... especially if you're not that good yet entitled enough to expect appreciation and respect simply for showing up ... on the streets.  You convert yourself from "a person" to a musician/artist/performer.. the moment you present yourself as such.. and from then on you're being addressed as such.. not for who you are as a person.. but as someone who is out there to entertain.. and the audience has some ideas for you how you can do that.. it could be a collaboration! :-D Tons of videos on youtube of street artists turning things around in a positive way.. "what happens when {insert song/piece of music} is being requested.."    Most street performers simply carry on when confronted with unsympathetic reactions. Some though, are good, show ability and can truly inspire; they're commanding respect and appreciation and my sympathy goes out to them.. not this crybaby artist who couldn't hack it on the streets.

Â @RD-tw7sxÂ  it's very hard to recognize when the singer can actually sing, she can sing, but post-production always involves slight autotune so some tones are just a little bit nicer to the ear.

Â @RD-tw7sxÂ  I'm giving you facts, it doesn't matter how good you are of a singer, your manager or the producer will always want some autotune to back it up, some notes just sound nicer when you shift them just a tiny bit. I'm not saying that she can't sing, she has her own style which I'm not a fan of, but she can hit the notes, but sometimes you just need the recording to be a little more polished which is just not humanly possible, so you use autotune, it's that simple.

Â @RD-tw7sxÂ  First of all, you can use autotune live, many people do it, even the best singers do it and almost all modern pop stars do it. Second, can you just get what I'm saying. I'm not saying her voice is super fake and that she autotuned the shit out of her vocals, I'm just saying that it's normal that people use autotune in studio, even to just give more texture to the voice, it's normal, everyone does that and you can't sometimes even tell it's there. She doesn't use autotune get super high notes or super low notes, it's just to maybe fix a small, insignificant mistake that nobody even notices but you just don't like. So for the last time, I'm not saying she autotuned the whole song, I'm just saying that autotuning a single word or a phrase is completely normal and there is no shame in doing, as long as you don't over use it.

She's great & I love how she's unapologetically herself & not the typical, cookie cutter sound or image of a popstar! I didn't get into music like this when I was her age because it was all manufactured by the same, like, 12 people for all the pop singers. I LOVE this new generation that's writing their own music! I'm not the age demographic this is marketed to, (let's just say Britney was still in a school girl skirt & pigtails when I was the age they're aiming to appeal to) but I love Billie Eilish, Bishop Briggs & a few others and I'll add Tones and I to that list!   I've always been, as different school teachers over the years always told my mom, "A square peg in a round hole" or that "I dance to the beat of my own drum" (The polite way of telling a parent their kid is odd, comparatively speaking)So most anything that goes against the grain I end up being fond of. I relate to her song Bad Child, even still at 36, I'm still trying to escape the role of the villain/scapegoat. Psh... whateva, I do what I want! Lol...What people think of me is none of my business & it usually says more about them than it does me!  Anyway, Her vocal & overall style definitely fits the bill of "out of the norm."  I love that her sound is 100% her voice, no effects or autotune! Didn't realize she's a pianist, even more respect! Okay I got carried away, I'm done now....lol
